	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Authorities in Senegal reduce prices of basic necessities </h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Senegal Minister of Commerce Amadou Niang announced in a communiqué on 2 February 2011 that the prices of most basic household necessities will be reduced by 10-15%. The measure, which entered into force on 4 February 2011, applies to prices of main staple food and sensitive commodities such as sugar, rice, concentrated tomatoes, oil and milk. In order to enforce this policy, it was decided to amend the law on freedom of prices in favour of a system of price controls based on prevailing international prices.</p><p>With this price-control policy, the government of Senegal hopes to prevent vendors from setting artificially high prices with high profit margins. According to the new price-control regime, vendors are obliged to display prices of goods in marketplaces.</p><p>However, Ascosen, the association of consumers in Senegal, has expressed dissatisfaction with the new policy, as they fear it will not be enough to solve the problem of high prices for basic food commodities. According to Ascosen’s president, Momar Ndaw, the government should bring down value-added tax to the 5% level permitted by WAEMU.</p><p>Senegal’s government is one of seven West African governments who have adopted price controls in response to high global food prices. Other policy measures adopted by these governments include:</p>
<ul>

<li>the lowering of taxes;</li>

<li>the introduction of price subsidies;</li>

<li>the provisions of subsidised agricultural inputs;</li>

<li>the introduction of export bans and tariff reductions; </li>

<li>expanded support to food reserve holdings.</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
