				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Food security is a politically sensitive issue in West Africa, as elsewhere. Many governments seek to protect local food production with measures which go beyond the ECOWAS and WAEMU common external tariffs for agricultural products. Price controls, consumer subsidies and input subsidies are less controversial at the international level than the use of trade-policy tools, such as import licensing or restrictions and export bans. However, with limited financial resources West African governments are likely to continue to make use of a range of policy tools in response to high and volatile prices, despite existing intra-regional and potential inter-regional policy commitments.</p>
		</div>
		
